04201nam a22006855i 9780691187617DE-B159720190523123322.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||190523s2018    nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97806911876177 a10.1515/97806911876172doi  a(DE-B1597)501893  a(OCoLC)1076413967  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 4aDK557 7aHIS0320002bisacsh 7aLIT0042402bisacsh04a809.933247212221 aBuckler, Julie A., eauthor.10aMapping St. Petersburg :bImperial Text and Cityshape /cJulie A. Buckler. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2018] 4cÂ©2005  a1 online resource   atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tIllustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tChapter One. Petersburg Eclecticism, Part I: City as Text -- tChapter Two. Petersburg Eclecticism, Part II: Literary Form and Cityshape -- tChapter Three. Armchair Traveling: Russian Literary Guides to St. Petersburg -- tChapter Four. Stories in Common: Urban Legends in St. Petersburg -- tChapter Five. Literary Centers and Margins: Palaces, Dachas, Slums, and Industrial Outskirts -- tChapter Six. Meeting in the Middle: Provincial Visitors to St. Petersburg -- tChapter Seven. The City's Memory: Public Graveyards and Textual Repositories -- tConclusion. Timely Remembering and the Tricentennial Celebration -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex  aPushkin's palaces or Dostoevsky's slums? Many a modern-day visitor to St. Petersburg has one or, more likely, both of these images in mind when setting foot in this stage set-like setting for some of the world's most treasured literary masterpieces. What they overlook is the vast uncharted territory in between. In Mapping St. Petersburg, Julie Buckler traces the evolution of Russia's onetime capital from a "conceptual hierarchy" to a living cultural system--a topography expressed not only by the city's physical structures but also by the literary texts that have helped create it. By favoring noncanonical works and "underdescribed spaces," Buckler seeks to revise the literary monumentalization of St. Petersburg--with Pushkin and Dostoevsky representing two traditional albeit opposing perspectives--to offer an off-center view of a richer, less familiar urban landscape. She views this grand city, the product of Peter the Great's ambitious vision, not only as a geographical entity but also as a network of genres that carries historical and cultural meaning. We discover the busy, messy "middle ground" of this hybrid city through an intricate web of descriptions in literary works; nonfiction writings such as sketches, feuilletons, memoirs, letters, essays, criticism; and urban legends, lore, songs, and social practices--all of which add character and depth to this refurbished imperial city.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Mai 2019) 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Russian & Former Soviet Union.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780691187617zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780691187617.jpg  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA14ALL  aPDA16SSH  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA1ALL  aPDA2  aPDA2HUM  aPDA5EBK  aPDA7ENG  aPDA9PRIN